:::summary
Ludwig van Beethoven (1770–1827) was a German composer whose nine symphonies, thirty-two piano sonatas, sixteen string quartets, and the *Missa Solemnis* stand as the supreme achievements of Western classical music. He bridged the Classical and Romantic eras, transforming music from elegant entertainment into profound spiritual expression. That he composed his greatest works — including the Ninth Symphony — in total deafness ranks among the most extraordinary feats in the history of human creativity.
:::

